My main motivation for attending HackNC is to learn how to manage a short-term project (both business and programming aspects) and transform it into a working idea with the support of fellow teammates. Alongside a team of 3 other like-minded students, I would like to start an algorithm that determines genes responsible for a person's susceptibility to mental illness. While I have researched this topic before and understand that such an algorithm takes more time to develop, piecing the fundamental "bare bones" together while learning hands-on skills working with a team would be unparalleled. My team members are all interested in some field of BME and bioinformatics, so having like-minded perspectives and allowing each person to contribute to the table makes the hackathon process unique. I would also like to synthesize our minds to develop some product that would be useful for a future start-up development, mainly one used in healthcare that supports the health of developers and reduces physical strains on them while sitting at the desktop all day. I also have an idea to create a more sustainable Neti Pot for chronic sufferers of congestion modeled off the current design.

At HackNC2015!: Based on my experience in the Internet of Things, I would like to explore the possibility of employing wearable and other devices to provide basic first aid in cases of health emergencies. The wearable tech would first detect the health emergency through the user's vital signs. Based on all the data collected, specific to the user and the public in general, a probabilistic model would be built of what the emergency could be. This model is then sent to the user's physician who is asked to approve of the treatment to be provided. I would like to start with simple treatments, like providing glucose in cases of hypoglycemia, and then move on to more complicated tasks. These would be executed by a drone. At HackNC, I aim to start with building the basic framework for collecting reliable data, building the probabilistic model and relaying it to the physician and activating the drone.

There’s an ongoing debate about the benefits and impact of hackathon culture, where people from different backgrounds (designers, coders, business people, artists, etc.) come together and work on projects in a condensed time-frame, and how these hackathons are avoiding putting forward impactful solutions to issues like poverty, unemployment, politics etc and they're right. Hackathons don't allow for making revolutionary changes like reducing poverty, reforming politics or improving education. However, they allow people to make small dents in some of the most intractable problems, provide invaluable connections, mentorship, experiential learning, resources that allow the participants to take action in their own communities. And that is exactly what I intend to get out of HackNC.
I love making things. The thrill of having an idea and see it come to life is what I love about Hackathons and what better place to enjoy that thrill than at HackNC where not only will i meet some of the smartest people but also get a chance to be mentored by some of the most influential people. For the past 2 summers I worked at a boy scout summer camp and I've always wanted to map out each individual tent there, Unfortinately, I need an exteremely accurate GPS equipment to do this, so right now I'm limited to just doing rough trails and outlines. Currently I'm working on outline the campsites.

Along with this, I would like to map out the whole camp using a 360 camera, which would allow you to use a VR headset or just a computer to explore all the trails and campsites.

A lot, honestly. I'm hoping not only to learn more technical areas (ie. languages, API's), but also to learn how to develop actual products. A lot of the programming I have done and projects I have worked on were always left incomplete - the idea was great, but as soon as things went from idea to actual code, team members would drop out, time would run out, funding would go away. With my first hackathon, I hope that the time constraint, as well as working with people who are just as dedicated as I am, will result in the true foundation of an actual product, and that  I will learn how to actually develop not just code. I'm also hoping to learn how quickly I can pick things up; I've always assumed I was a fast learner, but hacknc is a completely different ball-game, and I hope to see how quickly I can learn a new language, API, or style of programming.

It can become your on-the-go device! 

Most importantly, I also see myself making an app in near future that can handle large volumes of text related with a specialty field. While working with Linguavista, I realized that there are hundreds of businesses around the world that are in need of fast, accurate and unique translations. For example, some of the leading Forex brokers operate in as many as 30 languages, powered by daily human translation, which costs a lot of time and money. We will be able to subdue the huge operating costs if we are able to develop an interactive solution.
